    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "`Ctrl+Space` is exactly the same as `Ctrl-Escape` for a terminal. (On Windows, not necessarily, but prompt-toolkit assumes internally a Vt100 terminal, because this is the most common.)\n\nBy default, we use Emacs key bindings, which is also what readline does. (Readline does not implement all Emacs key bindings, this one for instance is not supported by readline.)\nBut in Emacs, pressing this key sequence will enter selection mode.\n\n`pgcli` attached a custom key binding to `ControlSpace`: https://github.com/dbcli/pgcli/blob/master/pgcli/key_bindings.py#L65\n\nI leave it up to the IPython core developers to decide what should happen when this is pressed. Maybe it can be configurable. In prompt-toolkit itself, this won't change for now.\n\nFYI: Emacs style copy/paste key bindings are as follows:\n- `CtrlSpace`: Enter selection mode.\n- `Ctrl-W`: Cut\n- `Meta-W`: Copy\n- `Ctrl-Y`: Paste\n- `Ctrl-C >`: Indent selection\n- `Ctrl-C <`: Unindent selection\n- `Ctrl-G`: Cancel selection mode.\n\nBy the way, people really use these key bindings, e.g.:\nhttps://github.com/xonsh/xonsh/issues/1074#issuecomment-223625302\n\nEdit: added the key bindings for indent/unindent: these can be useful in particular when working with larger chunks of input.\n"
  },
