    "updated_at": "2016-06-09T10:38:36Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "While the default mode of readline is emacs-like, it's a very reduced set of shortcuts which many of us (myself included) tend to think of as 'terminal shortcuts', because readline is so ubiquitous. So implementing more of the emacs shortcuts is a clear win for Emacs users, but more dubious for those of us who are neither familiar with emacs nor such keen vi users that we change the editing mode.\n\nMaybe there should be an 'emacs-lite' editing mode which disables some of these less familiar emacs features? On the other hand, having the shortcuts there allows us to start using them if we learn them.\n\n@klonuo why did you hit Ctrl-Space? I don't think that was a shortcut in IPython before - were you expecting it to do something, running on muscle memory from another program, or just hitting a wrong key by mistake?\n\nAnother approach would be to add a bottom bar which, in selection mode, would change to say e.g. \"Selection mode; Ctrl-G to exit\". That's probably something that we'd do after 5.0, though.\n"
  },
